JUST a day after Transport Minister Dipuo Peters revealed that KZN had the most accidents this festive season, the province&rsquo;s roads claimed more lives of innocent people.Five people died and scores were injured on Wednesday in three different taxi accidents.Peters had on Tuesday revealed that Limpopo has so far recorded the highest number of road fatalities since the beginning of December followed by Mpumalanga and KZN.Three people succumbed to their injuries early on Wednesday during a taxi accident on the N2 in Zinkwazi, north coast of KZN.Netcare 911 spokesman Chris Botha said reports from the scene indicated that the taxi veered off the road, overturned and slammed into the pillars of a bridge.Two more people died in the evening on the N3 north on the roadside stop in Harrismith.Botha said speculation indicated that the taxi the two people were travelling in could have been struck by a truck. &ldquo;A two-month-old baby and the driver of the taxi tragically died on impact. Ten other commuters sustained injuries and were treated at the scene before being transported to hospital,&rdquo; said Botha.He added that 14 people were injured in another taxi accident in Harrismith. The taxi was travelling from Kokstad to an unknown destination in the Free State when they slammed into the rear of a truck.On the Zinkwazi accident, police spokeswoman Captain Nqobile Gwala said: &ldquo;A case of culpable homicide is being investigated by KwaDukuza SAPS. Circumstances surrounding the incident are being investigated.&rdquo;